\b \cf0 Not Integral For Enjoyment
\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720

\fs28 \cf0 - Though I believe the meta concerns of this project are extremely important, there will be plenty of people who do not have the time, or know-how, for interacting with them. People who are 
\i au fait 
\i0 with ARGs and other transmedia projects will lap it up. If we can encourage others to join in with this new way of interacting with books, that will be excellent, but we cannot make wider participation necessary for enjoyment. Some people may just wish to view the efforts of others, and we should make this easy to do, and others may only want to interact with story. However, we must remember that the whole 
\i point 
\i0 of this project is to disperse narrative, to make it ergodic, and non-trivial. There needs to be a willingness for effort on the part of every reader, though, even if the intensity of that effort may vary from person to person.
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720

\b\fs28 \cf0 \
The Nature Of Canon
\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720

\fs28 \cf0 - Meta concerns naturally weaken the barriers of canon. Player contributions are important to this project, but giving them control is dangerous, as they can alter the experience for others in negative ways. The amount of canon democracy we allow is dependent on the story and how much we want the players to determine the culture of the Institute outside their department. Fan fiction is encouraged, but visibility to others in an official sense needs to be considered.
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720

\b\fs28 \cf0 \
The Player Experience
\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720

\fs28 \cf0 - Players like to shut off some personalities and inhabit others for a while. Roleplaying is important to many people. The meta concerns give them a chance to open up their singleplayer roleplaying (which, despite some opinion, is important for escape, self-identification, and mental health) and present their personas to others in a way that they cannot hurt each other\'92s fictions, but only interact positively. The Institute employs people who enjoy this absurdity - playing up to these grand titles, empowering them in their weakness. Players become part of an \'93ultracult\'94, a way to show uniqueness in an age of corporate identity and rising population. 
\fs24 \

\fs28 - Players will form niches, task forces, groups and alliances. They are not random, and should be encouraged. The differences between them become inherent and self-reinforcing. Their default position is one of defence, and so forming groups should come naturally to them. The drive is forward, with complication, as some players will set themselves against others. The department fights its decay from within to survive and complete this change that they are instigating.
