\fs28 \cf0 Jam With Chrome
\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720

\fs28 \cf0 A HTML5 (I assume?) experiment by Google, where people can play digital musical instruments, in their browser, using their mouse and keys. They can switch between instruments on the fly, and invite friends in to join them. This social experiment shows that sharing high-tech, accessible games is much easier on the web nowadays, and can be implemented in a way that makes it easy for people to share what they do with these tools with their friends. 
\fs24 \

\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720

\b \cf0 Myst Journals
\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720

\fs28 \cf0 Low-tech paper journals kept by players of the PC puzzle game Myst. These were often shared physically with local friends, as well as on the web when image-uploading became less of a headache. Fez, the recent Xbox 360 puzzle game, had a renaissance of people creating Tumblogs of these journals in which players attempted to work out the codes hidden in the game. What this shows is the drive of many players to use their own tools, outside of the game, to solve the more pressing, deep puzzles. Obviously, this does not apply to everyone who plays the game, or even the majority, but it reminds one of the adage to 
\i never treat your audience like idiots.
\i0  They do not need to be handheld through the experience, in case one small obstacle causes them to leave. This is the \'93Anti-Smaug\'94, or \'93Attention Deficit\'94 of which people are terrified on the Web at the moment.
